@kushagraThapar My current understanding is that, when we call write, the message will be queued in the out buffer, but it is not for sure that the message will be written to the socket. Netty will decide when to flush the message out, so that is why we do not have to call flush in our code.
@moderakh  Yea, make sense, and those are good tests to do for this change.
@kushagraThapar  @moderakh  I think I will revert this change for now, so this PR only contains style/renaming change,  and I will have a separate PR for this change and to investigate more about it.
